Workers at the Federal Capital Territory Administration (FCTA) are not finding it easy to cope with life, due to non-payment of January salary, which has affected their morale and productivity. The result of this delay is low-key activities, grudges, disquiet and lackluster attitudes among workers, which has equally affected visitors to the administration. Investigation conducted by LEADERSHIP revealed that staff working for the administration must have spent their savings during the Christmas and new year periods and are faced with financial challenges. A staff of the administration, Mohammed told our reporter that the delay has really affected the mood, productivity and performance of average worker of the administration, especially at this period of the year, as many have not been able to pay for their children school fees, rent and other engagements. “We returned from the Christmas and new year break, having spent our savings during the period, only to face the delay in the payment of our January salary. This delay has really affected our calculation as many workers have not been able to pay their children’s school fees and house rent.” Our reporter also gathered that the delay in salary payment is not unconnected with the new Integrated Payroll and Personnel Information System (IPPIS), which was adopted by the administration. “There is also the fear that the screening for the IPPIS process might continue till the end of March before the salary would be paid, which some workers have as described harsh and unacceptable. “Many of us are just managing with the little cash in our hands and waiting until the end of this exercise. But we are worried that the process is taking too long, because we heard that the process will end in March. This is not acceptable to many of us here.” 